name: GDPR Readiness Assessment - ISO 27001 annotated - 2.0.0
description: Assess your state of readiness to the GDPR and identify the areas where work is still required with tips and annotations linking to the ISO 27001 standard
welcomeText:
Welcome to the GDPR Readiness Assessment (ISO 27001 annotated)!

The GDPR went into effect on 25 May 2018 and companies around the world are still working on implementing structural changes to get compliant with the new EU data protection rules.


This readiness assessment will allow you to get an idea of your state of readiness for the GDPR and identify the areas where work is still required.


The assessment also includes tips and annotations linking to the ISO 27001 standard for organisations that hold certification to that standard.


There is significant common ground between the GDPR and ISO 27001 requirements. Although they come from different perspectives, ISO 27001 and the GDPR at their core are about reducing risk to people and organisations caused by misuse of personal data, with demonstrable overlap in both principles and requirements.


On the one hand, ISO 27001 focuses on reducing risks to information security by compelling organisations to produce information security management systems that are continuously maintained and improved. On the other hand, the GPDR focuses on reducing risks for data subjects by providing them with rights, placing clear privacy responsibilities on organisations processing personal data, and holding them accountable through legal and administrative enforcement mechanisms.


IAPP and OneTrust published a white paper: "IAPP-OneTrust Research: Bridging ISO 27001 to GDPR"to show how the ISO 27001 information security management framework correlates to the goals, objectives, and even specific requirements of the GDPR. It is a tool for security and privacy professionals to use for improved communication and mutual understanding. The paper is available here: https://onetrust.com/resources/bridging-iso-gdpr-research-report/



--

OneTrust products, content and materials are for informational purposes only and not for the purpose of providing legal advice. You should contact your attorney to obtain advice with respect to any particular issue. OneTrust materials do not guarantee compliance with applicable laws and regulations.

sections.name: Scope: Does GDPR apply to your organisation?

questions.content: Does your organisation process personal data (whether by automated means or as part of a paper filing system)?
questions.hint: If you have at least one employee, you likely process their personal data (such as their name)

questions.content: Is your organisation located in the European Union?
Is your organisation located outside the EU AND does it offer goods or services (for free or not) to individuals residing in the EU?
questions.friendlyName: Organisation outside EU and targets EU market

questions.content: Is your organisation located outside the EU AND does it monitor the behaviour of EU residents (for behaviour taking place in the EU)?
questions.friendlyName: Organisation outside EU monitors EU residents
questions.description: This usually applies if your website employs advertising technology to target and retarget, track or profile EU data subjects.

questions.content: Is your organisation located outside the EU, but has an establishment in the EU with some processing activity related to that EU establishment?
questions.friendlyName: Organisation outside EU and establishment in EU
questions.description: For example: your HQ is located in a country outside the EU and you have an establishment in an EU country (e.g. a subsidiary, a branch). The HQ plans on deploying a global data base for its HR activities, which will involve flow of personal data.

questions.content: Does your organisation have fewer than 250 employees?
Have you made a list of all of your organisation's processing activities?
questions.description: ISO 27001: ISO 27001 Clause 8 requires organisations to develop and maintain appropriate safeguards for organisational assets. Specifically, Clause 8.1 requires that organisations identify and clearly label important data assets. This inventory protocol includes requirements for clear definitions of ownership and acceptable uses for the data. Clause 8.2 continues by requiring data sensitivity classifications, labeling, and access controls based upon these sensitivity levels. Consider leveraging this existing work.

questions.content: Have you identified for each processing activity the activities where your organisation acts as a controller and those for which it acts as a processor?
questions.hint: Even if you mostly act as a processor, you are always the controller with respect to your employee data

questions.content: For the record of processing activity where you act as a controller, does your record include ALL of the following:
questions.friendlyName: Information to be included in controller records
questions.description:
• the name and contact details of your organisation,
  • the purposes of the processing,
  • a description of the categories of data subjects and of the categories of personal data (e.g. employee data, customer data),
  • the categories of recipients to whom the personal data have been or will be disclosed,
  • Any transfer of personal data to a third country of international organisation (if applicable),
  • the time limits for erasure for the different categories of data (where possible), and
  • a general description of the technical and organisational security measures?

ISO 27001: Control A.8: Information assets shall be inventoried and classified; asset owners shall be assigned, with procedures defined for acceptable data use, labelling, and handling. This is only a starting point. You still need to include the required records in Article 30(1) such as the purposes of the processing.

questions.content: For the record of processing activity where you act as a processor, does your record of categories of processing activities include all of the following:
questions.friendlyName: Information to be included in processor records
questions.description:
• the name and contact details of your organisation (processor),
  • the categories of processing carried out on behalf of each controller,
  • any transfer of personal data to a third country or international organisation (if applicable, and identify the country if a country outside the EEA), and,
  • where possible a general description of the technical and organisational security measures?

ISO 27001: Control A.8: Information assets shall be inventoried and classified; asset owners shall be assigned, with procedures defined for acceptable data use, labelling, and handling. This is only a starting point. You still need to include the required records in Article 30(2) such as the categories of processing carried out on behalf of each controller.

questions.content: Are the records of processing activities or categories of processing activities in writing (including in electronic form)?
ISO 27001 Internal Discussion Items
questions.description: Read the full white-paper: IAPP-OneTrust Research: Bridging ISO 27001 to GDPR

sections.name: Principles relating to the processing of personal data and legal basis for processing

questions.content: Do you collect personal data only for specified, explicit and legitimate purposes?
questions.description:
In other words, for only one legal purpose, and you are transparent about what this purpose is (in your privacy notice for example).
For example: Collecting personal data of job applicants via a form on the career page of your website. The purpose here would be HR recruiting.

questions.content: Do you have secondary uses for personal data that you have collected?
questions.description: This would occur if you processed personal data for a purpose other than the one why you collected the personal data in the first place and which would be incompatible with it.

questions.content: Do you only collect the personal data that are adequate and relevant for the purposes for which they are processed?
Do you collect personal data that is accurate, and where necessary, keep it up to date so that all personal data you process are accurate?
Do you keep personal data only for the duration necessary for the purpose for which you are processing it?
Have you identified which legal basis you rely on for each one of your processing activities?

sections.name: Processing of special categories of personal data

questions.content: Do you process any of the following type of personal data?
questions.description:
Personal data revealing:

  • Racial or ethnic origin
  • Political opinions
  • Religious or philosophical beliefs
  • Trade union membership
  • Genetic data
  • Biometric data for authentication (uniquely identifying a person)
  • Data concerning health
  • Data concerning someone's sex life or sexual orientation

questions.content: Do you process personal data about children below 16 in the context of the offering of information society services?
questions.description:
Information society services refers to any service normally provided for remuneration, at a distance (meaning that the service is provided without the parties being simultaneously present), by electronic means (meaning that the service is sent initially and received at its destination by means of electronic equipment for the processing (including digital compression) and storage of data, and entirely transmitted, conveyed and received by wire, by radio, by optical means or by other electromagnetic means and at the individual request of a recipient of services (meaning that the service is provided through the transmission of data on individual request).
Examples of information society services are:

  • online shops
  • live or on-demand streaming services,
  • companies providing access to communication networks.

questions.content: Do any of the following apply to you?
questions.description:
• You are a public authority or body (and NOT a court acting in its judicial capacity);
  • Your core activities consist of processing operations which, by virtue of their nature, their scope and/or their purposes, require regular and systematic monitoring of data subjects on a large scale;
  • Your core activities consist of processing on a large scale of special categories of data or personal data relating to criminal convictions and offences

questions.content: If you have designated a DPO, does he/she have sufficient professional qualities, knowledge of data protection law and practices and the ability to fulfill his/her tasks?
If you have a DPO, have you published his/her contact details?
questions.friendlyName: Publish contact details of the DPO

questions.content: If you have a DPO, have you communicated his/her contact details to the appropriate supervisory authority?
questions.friendlyName: Communicate contact details of DPO to SA

questions.content: If you have a DPO, is the DPO properly and in a timely manner involved in all issues related to the protection of personal data?
questions.friendlyName: DPO involvement in issues related to personal data

questions.content: If you have a DPO, is the DPO provided with sufficient resources to carry out his/her tasks and maintain his/her expert knowledge?
questions.friendlyName: Sufficient resources given to the DPO

questions.content: If you have a DPO, is he/she acting truly independently?
questions.description: According to the WP29 guidelines, this means that, in fulfilling their tasks, DPOs must not be instructed how to deal with a matter, for example, what result should be achieved, how to investigate a complaint or whether to consult the supervisory authority. Furthermore, they must not be instructed to take a certain view of an issue related to data protection law, for example, a particular interpretation of the law.

questions.content: If you have a DPO, is the DPO bound by secrecy or confidentiality with respect to his/her performance of his/her tasks?
If you have a DPO, is the DPO responsible for ALL of the following:
questions.description:
• inform and advise your organisation and the employees who carry out processing of their obligations pursuant to GDPR and other applicable data protection laws;
  • monitor compliance with the GDPR and other applicable data protection laws and with the policies of your organisation in relation to the protection of personal data, including the assignment of responsibilities, awareness-raising and training of staff involved in processing operations, and the related audits;
  • provide advice where requested as regards the data protection impact assessment and monitor its performance;
  • cooperate with the supervisory authority;
  • act as the contact point for the supervisory authority on issues relating to processing, including the prior consultation referred to in Article 36, and to consult, where appropriate, with regard to any other matter.

sections.name: Data Protection by design and by default (ISO 27001 annotated)

questions.content: Do you have internal processes in place to ensure that proper safeguards are integrated into the different processing activities?
questions.description:
This includes implementing appropriate technical and organisational measures for ensuring that, by default, only personal data which are necessary for each specific purpose of the processing are processed.
In practice, it could mean having relevant questions in a data protection impact assessment to identify all processing of personal data that would occur in the context of a product or service you want to launch.
ISO 27001: Clauses 5 and 6 contain multiple requirements designed to develop and maintain an adaptive security framework while identifying and mitigating operational risks. Combined, these clauses emphasise the importance of establishing a foundational framework that allows for the testing and safeguarding of processing actions. Consider utilising what has been built to meet these requirements as a way to address the need under Article 25 to incorporate security and privacy principles into products and processes from the outset and throughout implementation.

questions.content: ISO 27001 Internal Discussion Items
questions.description: Read the full white-paper: IAPP-OneTrust Research: Bridging ISO 27001 to GDPR

questions.content: Do you conduct a data protection impact assessment prior to starting any processing activity that is likely to result in a high risk for individuals?
questions.friendlyName: DPIA conducted for high risk processing activities

questions.content: If you have a DPO, is the DPO involved in the review of DPIAs?
Does your DPIA contain at least all of the following:
questions.description:
• a systematic description of the envisaged processing operations and the purposes of the processing, including, where applicable, the legitimate interest pursued by the controller;
  • an assessment of the necessity and proportionality of the processing operations in relation to the purposes;
  • an assessment of the risks to the rights and freedoms of data subjects; and
  • the measures considered to address the risks, including safeguards, security measures and mechanisms to ensure the protection of personal data and to demonstrate compliance with the GDPR taking into account the rights and legitimate interests of data subjects and other persons concerned.

questions.content: Do you have a process in place to ensure the DPIA is reviewed when there is a change of the risk represented by the processing activity?
questions.friendlyName: Review of DPIA when change of risk
questions.description:
For example, this could occur if your processing activity went from collecting personal data about 100 users to collecting data about 1000 users (in other words, the number of individuals concerned increases significantly).
ISO 27001 Control A.15.2.2. This control addresses the review of supplier relationship where there is a change in supplier provision of services. Consider using a similar process for your DPIA review when there is a change of risk.

questions.content: Has your organisation implemented technical and organisational measures that ensure the level of security is appropriate to the risk?
questions.friendlyName: Security measures appropriate to the risks
questions.description:
Those measures include:

  • the pseudonymisation and encryption of personal data;
  • the ability to ensure the ongoing confidentiality, integrity, availability and resilience of processing systems and services;
  • the ability to restore the availability and access to personal data in a timely manner in the event of a physical or technical incident;
  • a process for regularly testing, assessing and evaluating the effectiveness of technical and organisational measures for ensuring the security of the processing.

ISO 27001: Looking at your ISO 27001 risk assessment may be helpful here! Clause 6 calls for the creation of an information security risk assessment methodology, which includes the identification of risk levels and risk acceptance, the assignment of responsibility, plans for the treatment of identified security risks, and the setting of security objectives.

questions.content: ISO 27001 Internal Discussion Items
questions.description: Read the full white-paper: IAPP-OneTrust Research: Bridging ISO 27001 to GDPR

questions.content: Do you have a privacy notice (or several privacy notices) easily accessible to individuals in which you provide all of the following information:
questions.description:
• Identity and the contact details of the controller (and controller's representative, where applicable),
  • the contact details of the Data protection officer (where applicable),
  • the purposes of processing for which the personal data are intended and the legal basis for the processing,
  • where you rely on legitimate interest for a particular processing activity, the legitimate interests pursued by your organisation or a third party,
  • the recipients or categories of recipients of the personal data, if any (e.g. vendors you may be using to provide a particular service),
  • where applicable, the fact that transfer of personal data to a third country or international organisation occurs and which mechanism is being used for such transfer (e.g. Privacy Shield),
  • the period for which the personal data is being stored or criteria used to determine that period,
  • the existence of the rights that individuals have (including right of access, rectification, restriction of processing, object and the right to data portability),
  • the right to withdraw consent where consent is used as the legal basis,
  • the right to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority,
  • whether the provision of personal data by the individual is required by law or by a contract, or necessary to enter into a contract; whether the person is obligation to provide such personal data and the possible consequences if the personal data are not provided,
  • the existence of automated decision-making (including profiling), and if applicable, meaningful information about the logic involved, what it means for the person, and the consequences of such processing for the person
  • Information on secondary use, if secondary use is intended.

questions.content: Does your organisation enable individuals to exercise the rights they have under GDPR by informing individuals about those rights?
questions.description: For example, does your privacy notice explain how people can exercise their rights (e.g.by sending an email to a specific email address)?

questions.content: Do you have an internal policy in place describing how data subject requests are being handled within your organisation?
questions.friendlyName: Internal policy for data subject requests
questions.description:
This should include things like who is handling the request internally, what the process is, verify the person's identity if in doubt, implementing the request, respond to the individual within the appropriate timeline.
ISO 27001: The combination of data inventory, classification, and operating requirements from Clause 8 and Control A.8 empowers security with knowledge of the categories of data the organisation collects about data subjects and where the data lives. Control A.12: Operating procedures shall be documented.

questions.content: Do you have proper training in place for the employees that may receive data subject requests and those who will be in charge of handling them?
questions.friendlyName: Employee training for data subject rights
questions.description: ISO 27001: Control A.7.2.2 addresses relevant education and training that need to be provided to employees. Consider using that existing process and create a training specific to the handling of data subject rights to give to employees who will be receiving and/or handling requests.

questions.content: Are you aware of or did you verify the possible derogations that may exist in the jurisdiction in which you are located?
questions.description: The GDPR allows for Member States of the EU to pass laws to restrict the rights of data subjects and the related obligations that the controller has.

questions.content: ISO 27001 Internal Discussion Items
questions.description: Read the full white-paper: IAPP-OneTrust Research: Bridging ISO 27001 to GDPR

questions.content: ISO 27001 Control A.15: Supplier Relationships
questions.description: ISO 27001 includes vendor oversight and control as critical components of appropriate data security protocols.

questions.content: Prior to engaging a new vendor, do you conduct a vendor assessment to identify whether or not the vendor has appropriate technical and organisational measures to protect the personal data?
questions.description: ISO 27001: Control A.15 addresses security concerns where the organisation is vulnerable to vendor (“supplier”) access to personal data. It requires risk mitigation by limiting data access and by entering agreements to impose security responsibility and assign liability.

questions.content: Do you have a contract in place with your vendor which addresses ALL of the following:
questions.description:
• the subject matter and duration of the processing,
  • the nature and purpose of the processing activity,
  • the type of personal data and categories of data subject,
  • the obligations and rights of the controller?
  • that the processor must only act on the written instructions of the controller (unless required by law to act without such instructions) or include similar language,
  • require that the processor ensure that people processing the data are subject to a duty of confidence,
  • that the processor has appropriate security measures in place,
  • the use of subprocessors by the processor (those terms should require prior approval of controller or at least prior notification with the right for the controller to object to the use of a new subprocessor) and also require that processor impose the same data protection obligations to its subprocessor,
  • that the processor assist the data controller in providing subject access and allowing data subjects to exercise their rights under the GDPR,
  • that the processor assist the data controller in meeting its GDPR obligations in relation to the security of processing, the notification of personal data breaches and data protection impact assessments,
  • that the processor delete or return all personal data to the controller as requested by controller at the end of the contract,
  • a right for controller to audit processor's compliance with the data processing terms,
  • that nothing within the contract relieves the processor of its own direct responsibilities and liabilities under the GDPR; and reflect any indemnity that has been agreed?

ISO 27001: Control A.18.1 governs compliance with contractual requirements.

questions.content: ISO 27001 Internal Discussion Items
questions.description: Read the full white-paper: IAPP-OneTrust Research: Bridging ISO 27001 to GDPR

sections.name: Transfer of personal data outside the EEA

questions.content: Do any of your processing activities involve the transfer of personal data outside the EEA or to an international organisation?
questions.friendlyName: Transfer of personal data outside the EEA

questions.content: Do you have a proper mechanism you rely on for each transfer outside the EEA or to an international organisation?
questions.friendlyName: Mechanism for intl. transfer of personal data
questions.description:
For example:

  • An adequacy decision has been issued by the EU Commission for the country where you are transferring the personal data
  • You are self-certified to the Privacy Shield Framework (EU-US or Swiss-US)
  • You have standard contractual clauses in place
  • You have binding corporate rules

questions.content: Do you have proper mechanism in place to identify a security incident and have the DPO (or other person responsible for your GDPR programme) made aware of such incident?
questions.description: ISO 27001: Control A.16: Information security events shall be reported through the proper internal channels immediately, assessed to determine if they are “incidents,” documented, and investigated. ISO 27001 requires mechanisms both to quickly identify security incidents and to report them through the necessary established channels. This control (A.16) is designed to ensure a consistent and effective approach to the management of information security incidents, including communication on security events and weaknesses.

questions.content: When the organisation becomes aware of a security incident, is the DPO (or other person) involved to determine whether the incident constitutes a personal data breach under the GDPR?
questions.friendlyName: Determine if incident is a GDPR PDB

questions.content: When the organization becomes aware of a security incident, is the DPO (or other person) involved to determine if the organization is acting as a controller or processor in the context of that personal data breach?
questions.friendlyName: Controller or processor in the context of PDB

questions.content: Do you have a personal data breach plan in place that sets out the following:
questions.description:
• the process for investigating the personal data breach,
  • identifying the consequences,
  • implementing mitigating measures, and
  • the assessment to conduct in order to determine whether the personal data breach is unlikely to result in a risk to individuals affected by it?

ISO 27001: Looking at your ISO 27001 documented procedures for security incident management may be helpful here! (Control A.16).

questions.content: Where a notification to the supervisory authority is necessary, do you have proper processes in place to communicate all the following:
questions.description:
• a description of the nature of the personal data breach including where possible, the categories and approximate number of data subjects concerned and the categories and approximate number of personal data records concerned;
  • the name and contact details of the data protection officer or other contact point where more information can be obtained;
  • a description of the likely consequences of the personal data breach;
  • a description of the measures taken or proposed to be taken to address the personal data breach, including, where appropriate, measures to mitigate its possible adverse effects.

ISO 27001 Control A.18: Security management includes complying with legal, regulatory, and contractual obligations relating to information privacy.

questions.content: Where a notification to data subjects is necessary, do you have proper processes in place to communicate all of the following:
questions.description:
• the nature of the personal data breach
  • the name and contact details of the data protection officer or other contact point where more information can be obtained;
  • a description of the likely consequences of the personal data breach;
  • a description of the measures taken or proposed to be taken to address the personal data breach, including, where appropriate, measures to mitigate its possible adverse effects.

ISO 27001 Control A.18: Security management includes complying with legal, regulatory and contractual obligations relating to information privacy.

questions.content: Do you have processes in place to ensure that proper documentation regarding the personal data breach is kept?
questions.friendlyName: Keep proper documentation of personal data breach
questions.description:
The documentation should include:

  • the facts relating to the personal data breach
  • its effects, and
  • the remedial action taken.

The documentation should allow the supervisory authority to verify compliance with your obligations relating to a personal data breach.
ISO 27001 Control A.16: Information security events shall be documented.

questions.content: ISO 27001 Internal Discussion Items
questions.description: Read the full white-paper: IAPP-OneTrust Research: Bridging ISO 27001 to GDPR

questions.description:
Available here: https://onetrust.com/resources/bridging-iso-gdpr-research-report/
This whitepaper demonstrates how that collaboration can involve fewer pain points and be more productive by showing how the ISO 27001 information security management framework correlates to the goals, objectives, and even specific requirements of the GDPR. It is a tool for security and privacy professionals to use for improved communication and mutual understanding.

actionParameters.recommendation: See article 2 of GDPR

actionParameters.description: The GDPR applies to entities located in the European Union.
The GDPR probably applies to your entity.
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 3 of GDPR

actionParameters.description: The GDPR probably applies to your entity.
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 3 of GDPR

actionParameters.description: The GDPR probably applies to your entity, but for that processing activity only. Your organisation is not subject to GDPR simply by virtue of having an establishment in the EU. But the transfer of personal data of EU individuals to your organisation under certain data transfer mechanisms would impose compliance obligations on your organisation in respect of those personal data.
actionParameters.recommendation: See article 3 of GDPR

actionParameters.description:
The record keeping obligations do not apply to an enterprise or an organisation employing
fewer than 250 persons unless the processing it carries out is likely to result in a risk to the rights and freedoms of data subjects, the processing is not occasional, or the processing includes special categories of data as referred to in Article 9(1) or personal data relating to criminal convictions and offences referred to in Article 10.
actionParameters.recommendation:
Verify whether you fall under any of the exceptions and if not, it might be that you are not required to maintain those records. 

However, from a practical standpoint, note that having records of processing activities, data and asset inventories will make other areas of compliance easier to tackle.

actionParameters.description: This is part of the Article 30 requirement and this will help you with achieving compliance.
actionParameters.recommendation: Think about leveraging existing work. You may already have records for PCI compliance for example, or list of all your assets maintained by your IT/security team.

actionParameters.description: Records for processors and controllers under article 30 do not include the same information.
actionParameters.recommendation: You should conduct this analysis for each of your processing activities so that you can keep records with the proper information.

actionParameters.description: This is all the information that needs to be included in your records of processing activities as a controller.
actionParameters.recommendation:
Refer to Article 30(1) of GDPR.

Check whether the Supervisory Authority you are subject to has released a template for Article 30 record keeping. Some supervisory authorities (the CNIL (France), the ICO (UK), the GBA/APD (Belgium), and the German SA have issued templates for what they expect the records of processing activities to look like.

actionParameters.description: This is all the information that needs to be included in your records of processing activities as a processor.
actionParameters.recommendation:
Refer to Article 30(2) of GDPR.

Check whether the Supervisory Authority you are subject to has released a template for Article 30 record keeping. Some supervisory authorities (the CNIL (France), the ICO (UK), the GBA/APD (Belgium), and the German SA have issued templates for what they expect the records of processing activities to look like.

actionParameters.description: The records of controller and processor need to be in writing, including in electronic form.
actionParameters.recommendation: Article 30(3) of GDPR.

actionParameters.description: Personal data shall be: collected for specified, explicit and legitimate purposes and not further processed in a manner that is incompatible with those purposes; further processing for archiving purposes in the public interest, scientific or historical research purposes or statistical purposes shall, in accordance with Article 89(1), not be considered to be incompatible with the initial purposes (‘purpose limitation’).
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 5 of GDPR.

actionParameters.description: Personal data shall be: collected for specified, explicit and legitimate purposes and not further processed in a manner that is incompatible with those purposes; further processing for archiving purposes in the public interest, scientific or historical research purposes or statistical purposes shall, in accordance with Article 89(1), not be considered to be incompatible with the initial purposes (‘purpose limitation’).
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 5 of GDPR.

actionParameters.description: Personal data shall be: adequate, relevant and limited to what is necessary in relation to the purposes for which they are processed (‘data minimisation’).
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 5 of GDPR.

actionParameters.description: Personal data shall be: accurate and, where necessary, kept up to date; every reasonable step must be taken to ensure that personal data that are inaccurate, having regard to the purposes for which they are processed, are erased or rectified without delay (‘accuracy’).
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 5 of GDPR.

actionParameters.description:
Personal data shall be: kept in a form which permits identification of data subjects for no longer than is necessary for the purposes for which the personal data are processed; personal data may be stored for longer periods insofar as the personal data will be processed solely for archiving purposes in the public interest, scientific or historical research purposes or statistical purposes in accordance with Article 89(1) subject to implementation of the appropriate technical and organisational measures required by this Regulation in order to safeguard the rights and freedoms of the data subject
(‘storage limitation’).
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 5 of GDPR.
See Article 6 of GDPR.

actionParameters.description:
Article 9 of GDPR prohibits this type of processing unless an exception applies.  Processing of personal data revealing racial or ethnic origin, political opinions, religious or philosophical beliefs, or trade union membership, and the processing of genetic data, biometric data for the purpose of uniquely identifying a natural person, data concerning health or data concerning a natural person's 
sex life or sexual orientation shall be prohibited.
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 9(2) and make sure you have a proper way to process those special categories of data.

actionParameters.description: When relying on consent, in relation to the offer of information society services directly to a child, the processing of the personal data of a child shall be lawful where the child is at least 16 years old. Where the child is below the age of 16 years, such processing shall be lawful only if and to the extent that consent is given or authorised by the holder of parental responsibility over the child.
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 8 of GDPR. The GDPR also allows for member states to change the age for consent in this context, providing it does not go below 13. Check if there is a different age for children consent in the jurisdiction you are located, and keep track of the legislative process as this is most likely undergoing legislative process now or will be passed in the future.

actionParameters.description:
The controller and the processor shall designate a data protection officer in any case where:
(a) the processing is carried out by a public authority or body, except for courts acting in their judicial capacity;
(b) the core activities of the controller or the processor consist of processing operations which, by virtue of their nature, their scope and/or their purposes, require regular and systematic monitoring of data subjects on a large scale; or
(c) the core activities of the controller or the processor consist of processing on a large scale of special categories of data pursuant to Article 9 and personal data relating to criminal convictions and offences referred to in Article 10.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See article 37 of GDPR.

Check the WP29 guidelines on DPO available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612048

actionParameters.description:
Article 37(5) of GDPR:

The data protection officer shall be designated on the basis of professional qualities and, in particular, expert knowledge of data protection law and practices and the ability to fulfil the tasks referred to in Article 39.
actionParameters.recommendation: Check the WP29 guidelines on DPO available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612048

actionParameters.description:
Article 37(7) of GDPR: 

The controller or the processor shall publish the contact details of the data protection officer (...).
actionParameters.recommendation:
See Article 37(7) of GDPR.

Check the WP29 guidelines on DPO available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612048

actionParameters.description:
Article 37(7) of GDPR: 

The controller or the processor shall (...) communicate [the contact details of the DPO] to the supervisory authority.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See article 37(7) of GDPR.

Check the WP29 guidelines on DPO available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612048

actionParameters.description:
Article 38(1)

The controller and the processor shall ensure that the data protection officer is involved, properly and in a timely manner, in all issues which relate to the protection of personal data.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See article 38(1).

Check the WP29 guidelines on DPO available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612048

actionParameters.description:
Article 38(2):

The controller and processor shall support the data protection officer in performing the tasks referred to in Article 39 by providing resources necessary to carry out those tasks and access to personal data and processing operations, and to maintain his or her expert knowledge.
actionParameters.recommendation: Check the WP29 guidelines on DPO available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612048

actionParameters.description:
Article 38(3):

The controller and processor shall ensure that the data protection officer does not receive any instructions regarding the exercise of those tasks. He or she shall not be dismissed or penalised by the controller or the processor for performing his tasks. The data protection officer shall directly report to the highest management level of the controller or the processor.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See article 38(3).

Check the WP29 guidelines on DPO available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612048

actionParameters.description:
Article 38(5):

The data protection officer shall be bound by secrecy or confidentiality concerning the performance of his or her tasks, in accordance with Union or Member State law.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See article 38(5).

Check the WP29 guidelines on DPO available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612048

See article 39 of GDPR.

Check the WP29 guidelines on DPO available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612048

actionParameters.description: The concept of data protection by design and by default is now included in the GDPR. In its very basic form it means that you should assess and integrate data protection considerations at the outset of a new processing activity.
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 25 of GDPR.

actionParameters.description:
Article 35(1):

Where a type of processing in particular using new technologies, and taking into account the nature, scope,
context and purposes of the processing, is likely to result in a high risk to the rights and freedoms of natural persons,
the controller shall, prior to the processing, carry out an assessment of the impact of the envisaged processing
operations on the protection of personal data. A single assessment may address a set of similar processing operations
that present similar high risks.

Article 35(3):
A data protection impact assessment referred to in paragraph 1 shall in particular be required in the case of:
(a) a systematic and extensive evaluation of personal aspects relating to natural persons which is based on automated
processing, including profiling, and on which decisions are based that produce legal effects concerning the natural
person or similarly significantly affect the natural person;
(b) processing on a large scale of special categories of data referred to in Article 9(1), or of personal data relating to
criminal convictions and offences referred to in Article 10; or
(c) a systematic monitoring of a publicly accessible area on a large scale.
actionParameters.recommendation:
Implement some systematic process within your company having some threshold to assess whether there is a high risk associated with a particular processing activity, and have a proper DPIA questionnaire ready, if a full DPIA is necessary.

Check out the WP29 Guidelines on DPIA for more details (available at http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=611236).

actionParameters.description:
Article 35(2):

The controller shall seek the advice of the data protection officer, where designated, when carrying out a data protection impact assessment.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See article 35(2). 

Check out the WP29 Guidelines on DPIA for more details (available at http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=611236).

actionParameters.description:
Article 35(7):

The assessment shall contain at least:
(a) a systematic description of the envisaged processing operations and the purposes of the processing, including, where
applicable, the legitimate interest pursued by the controller;
(b) an assessment of the necessity and proportionality of the processing operations in relation to the purposes;
(c) an assessment of the risks to the rights and freedoms of data subjects referred to in paragraph 1; and
(d) the measures envisaged to address the risks, including safeguards, security measures and mechanisms to ensure the
protection of personal data and to demonstrate compliance with this Regulation taking into account the rights and
legitimate interests of data subjects and other persons concerned.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See article 35(7). 

Check out the WP29 Guidelines on DPIA for more details (available at http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=611236).

actionParameters.description:
Article 35(11):

Where necessary, the controller shall carry out a review to assess if processing is performed in accordance with the data protection impact assessment at least when there is a change of the risk represented by processing operations.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See article 35(11). 

Check out the WP29 Guidelines on DPIA for more details (available at http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=611236).

actionParameters.description:
Article 32(1):

Taking into account the state of the art, the costs of implementation and the nature, scope, context and purposes of processing as well as the risk of varying likelihood and severity for the rights and freedoms of natural persons, the controller and the processor shall implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure a level of security appropriate to the risk.
actionParameters.recommendation: See article 32 of GDPR.

actionParameters.description: All this information needs to be provided to the data subjects in cases where personal data is collected directly from the data subject.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See Article 13 of GDPR. Similar (but not fully identical) information needs to be provided to data subjects in cases where personal data about them are collected from another source. See Article 14 of GDPR for more details.

Check also Article 12 for relevant details on the right of information.

actionParameters.description:
Article 12(2):
The controller shall facilitate the exercise of data subject rights under Articles 15 to 22.
actionParameters.recommendation: You need to be transparent about data subject rights and give individuals an easy way to exercise their rights. Determine what method(s) you would like to use (e.g. include an email address in your privacy notice, embed a web form on your website for individuals to fill out) and implement it.

actionParameters.description: All nine data subject rights in GDPR require implementing policies and processes in your company to address how those requests will be handled.
actionParameters.recommendation: Draft and implement specific data subject rights policies and processes to address how data subject requests will be handled within your organization.

actionParameters.description: Although this is not required under GDPR, training your employees will be key in implementing data subject rights successfully within your organisation.
actionParameters.recommendation: Prepare appropriate training dedicated to the handling of data subject requests for the employees who will be receiving and handling those requests.

actionParameters.description: Data subject rights may be restricted by member states.
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 23 Data subject rights may be restricted by member states.for more details on derogations to data subject rights by member states.

actionParameters.description:
Article 28(1):

Where processing is to be carried out on behalf of a controller, the controller shall use only processors providing sufficient guarantees to implement appropriate technical and organisational measures in such a manner that processing will meet the requirements of this Regulation and ensure the protection of the rights of the data subject.
actionParameters.recommendation: Draft appropriate security questions to send to your vendors prior to hiring them to assess whether it offers a level of security appropriate to the risk based on the personal data the vendor will be processing.

actionParameters.description: Controllers and processors are now required under GDPR to have a contract in place to address certain data protection terms.
actionParameters.recommendation: See Article 28 for more details on what that contract needs to cover.

actionParameters.description:
When personal data is transferred outside the European Economic Area, special safeguards are foreseen to ensure that the protection travels with the data.

The GDPR offers a diversified toolkit of mechanisms to transfer data to third countries: adequacy decisions, standard contractual rules, binding corporate rules, certification mechanism, codes of conduct, so-called "derogations" etc.
actionParameters.recommendation: See chapter V of GDPR for more details.

actionParameters.description:
When personal data is transferred outside the European Economic Area, special safeguards are foreseen to ensure that the protection travels with the data.

The GDPR offers a diversified toolkit of mechanisms to transfer data to third countries: adequacy decisions, standard contractual rules, binding corporate rules, certification mechanism, codes of conduct, so-called "derogations" etc.
actionParameters.recommendation: Put in place an appropriate safeguard for all transfers of personal data outside the EEA. You may be relying on different ones for different processing activities (e.g. EU-US Privacy Shield, and standard contractual clauses).

actionParameters.description: It is important to be able to detect a security incident when it occurs so the possible adverse consequences can be mitigated as early as possible.
actionParameters.recommendation:
Implement a proper process, including designating a person responsible for such identification and reporting.

Check out the WP29 Guidelines on personal data breach available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612052

actionParameters.description:
The DPO (or other privacy champion) should be involved any time a security incident occurs, as he/she will need to determine whether the incident constitutes a personal data breach within the meaning of GDPR. 

This is important because notification to the supervisory authority and data subjects may be required within a strict timeline if the incident is considered a personal data breach under the GDPR.
actionParameters.recommendation: Check out the WP29 Guidelines on personal data breach available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612052

actionParameters.description:
Where there is a personal data breach, it is important to know whether you were acting as a controller or processor for the personal data affected, as your obligations differ. Processors are required to assist the controller in fulfilling their notification obligations, which means informing the controller without undue delay. 
Controllers are responsible for notifying the supervisory authority, where applicable, within 72 hours of having become aware of the breach.
actionParameters.recommendation: Check out the WP29 Guidelines on personal data breach available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612052

actionParameters.description: It is crucial to have a proper plan in place for when a breach occurs so you know what to do in this potentially stressful situation.
actionParameters.recommendation: Check out the WP29 Guidelines on personal data breach available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612052

actionParameters.description: This information would be required to include in the notification to the supervisory authority in cases where a notification would be required.
actionParameters.recommendation:
See Articles 33 for more details.

Check out the WP29 Guidelines on personal data breach available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612052

actionParameters.description: This information would be required to include in the notification to the data subjects, where a notification would be required.
actionParameters.recommendation: See article 34 of GDPR for more details.

actionParameters.description:
Article 33(5):
The controller shall document any personal data breaches, comprising the facts relating to the personal data
breach, its effects, and the remedial action taken. That documentation shall enable the supervisory authority to verify compliance with this Article.
actionParameters.recommendation: Check out the WP29 Guidelines on personal data breach available at: http://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/item-detail.cfm?item_id=612052
